        <title>Overview</title>
        <contents>&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Adding a Layer of Critical Thinking&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Lesson Modifications&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Questions Teachers Ask&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Language Needed To Express Critical Thinking&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Listen to audio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0120.mp3"&gt;ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0120.mp3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Audio transcript&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This section explores a variety of ways that we can foster development of critical thinking skills at all levels with adult ELLs. We look at lesson modifications that add a layer of critical thinking. We look at questioning strategies instructors can use that promote critical thinking. We also explore the language adult ELLs need to engage in those critical conversations. What are the words we need to use in English to synthesize ideas from a multiple sources? We start this section with a beginning-level-reading lesson.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
