        <title>Adding a Layer of Critical Thinking</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/Choua.png" width="250" height="393" alt="" style="float: right; margin: 5px 15px;" /&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Imagine that you came across the following reading text and accompanying questions in your book or curriculum.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Choua's New Job&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Choua Vang has a new job. Now Choua works at Family Mart. She works part time from 7:00 in the morning to noon. Now she can be with her two younger sisters and brother in the afternoon and then go to school to work on her English in the evening.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Choua usually helps her sister with homework in the afternoon. Sometimes they go to the playground near their house. They often help their mother. They wash clothes and help clean the house. Choua enjoys her new schedule.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Where does Choua work?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;What are her hours?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;How many brothers and sisters does she have?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;How does she help her mother?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Listen to audio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0130.mp3"&gt;ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0130.mp3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Audio transcript&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This kind of reading text and task is fairly common in ELA materials, isn’t it? How does it promote critical thinking? Were the teacher to have students look at the picture and title and make some predictions, learners could then read and compare what they learn to their own assumptions. Or if they did a pre-reading exercise about their job and personal schedule, they could compare Choua’s experiences to their own, which promotes some level of critical thinking. Although the questions are all wh-questions, they are generally display questions, that’s to say, those with only one right answer. They don’t require any interpretation on the part of the reader. Now let’s see how we can add a layer of critical thinking by using a simple graphic organizer, a line-up task, and questions that require some abstraction.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
