        <title>The Questions We Ask</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/instructor%20with%20learners.png" width="250" height="392" alt="" style="float: right; margin: 5px 15px;" /&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;The line of questioning added in place of a series of comprehension questions helps learners to:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Analyze the relationship between ideas&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Categorize and sequence information&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Find evidence to support a claim&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Recognize a chronology&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Listen to audio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0160.mp3"&gt;ELL_MOD1_UNIT4_0160.mp3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Audio transcript&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you chose all five skills, you were right! Ordering themselves and then responding to the questions really heightens the level of critical thinking with this reading. Learners have to analyze the relationship between ideas as they categorize and sequence the activities in Choua’s day. Was there one chronology for Choua’s afternoon activities? Do we know if she does those activities every day? No, Choua and her siblings had to make a decision whether to stand in a particular order or not. Through the questions, the group can debate whether it’s wise to do homework before or after going to the playground. They can discuss their own beliefs about roles in the family and chores to be done and how frequently (we don’t usually wash clothes every day, for example). A text may not spell out these relationships between ideas, but we draw on logic and our own experiences to interpret even a simple text like this. These teaching strategies draw learners’ attention to these features. The simple word “now” signals the change in Choua’s life and helps to explain how important it is that she can now be with her siblings. That and the fact that she can manage work and family and still study English may be the evidence of why she likes her new schedule.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
